Fifth - Scott Morrison's approach shirks the main increase to mandatory care minutes.

Inadequate staffing levels are central to many of the quality care problems in residential aged care.

This is core to improving care and clinical standards yet it's not happening.

Third - the Royal Commission strongly recommended we fully clear the Home Care waitlist.

The Govt have now promised 80,000 packages.

But there are 100,000 older Australians on the waitlist and many more get added every year.

The maths simply don't add up.

Second - Morrison is spending $3.2 billion increasing the basic daily fee for residential providers but doing nothing to ensure that money is tied to better food and care.

Two thirds of our aged care residents are malnourished or at risk of malnourishment.  It's an emergency.

First - nothing will really change without reform to the workforce.

The low level of private sector R&D spend is also critical. We are massively behind leading countries and we need to do better.

But by cutting nearly $2 billion out of the RDTI, the Morrison Government is seeking to make Australia *less* attractive for R&D investment #auspol

It’s the pointy end of a longer term issue.

As of last year there were 2000 fewer people working in government-funded R&D programs than there were in the mid-1990s.

Universities Australia reported in 2019 that government spending on R&D was the lowest it’s been in four decades.

The picture of government R&D spending in Australia is grim and has only gotten worse under the Coalition.

Just between 2015-16 and 2017-18, government R&D expenditure fell 19% in real terms. #auspol

Australia’s national spending on R&D is about 1.8% of GDP. 

World leading countries are spending more than 4%, and the OECD average is well above ours at about 2.4%. 

In fact, 2016-17 was the first year R&D spending in Australia actually went backwards.

There’s a basic problem in Australia that we can’t avoid: We’re not investing enough in R&D.

R&D is our pipeline for economic growth and a high standard of living for the future.

But this Govt wants to rip nearly $2 billion out of R&D. #auspol

Despite nearly 30 years of economic growth until this year, national economic policy seems to have left these women behind.

Their situation is not inevitable. There is a lot – *a lot* – we can do to give these women more choices.

There's a big group of women out there who are not being listened to - who are getting ignored by the Morrison Government, treated as though they are invisible.

If we want to do better by these women, we have to see them, and we have to hear them.

These women are likely to work in hospitality and sales, and as cleaners and laundry workers. Their largest area of employment is as carers, aides and community services workers. https://t.co/lHZkkgY9Oz

These women are the unseen human face of Australia’s underemployment crisis. 

They are young, they live in regional towns and the outer suburbs of our big cities, and they did not study much beyond high school.

Before COVID, the underutilisation rate (jobless rate + underemployment) of lower skilled women on the Central Coast and North Coast of NSW was more than 40 percent.
 
In Tasmania it was above 35 percent. In Greater Perth and South Eastern Queensland almost 30 percent. #auspol https://t.co/jf2DFwWEIM

If you fly over the underemployment numbers at a national level, you can't see the dire situation for these women at ground level.

Inadequate hours of work is an endemic, longstanding part of their working lives. The labour market is just not meeting their needs. Not even close.

The share of women in the labour market who did not study beyond high school or have a Certificate II or III is 2.8m Australian women. Of those women, almost 600,000 were either under-employed or unemployed before COVID. https://t.co/fp987JPCbR

The COVID recession is having a particularly devastating impact on Australian women in lower skilled work - but new data shows us that these women were already doing it really tough before COVID hit.

What will the future of work look like for these women?
